5|$|Romeo and Juliet borrows from a {{tradition}} of tragic love stories dating back to antiquity. One of these is Pyramus and Thisbe, from Ovid's Metamorphoses, which contains parallels to Shakespeare's story: the lovers' parents despise each other, and Pyramus falsely <b>believes</b> <b>his</b> lover Thisbe is dead. The Ephesiaca of Xenophon of Ephesus, written in the 3rd century, also contains several similarities to the play, including {{the separation of the}} lovers, and a potion that induces a deathlike sleep.|$|E
